<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Henry, Alexander. Travels in the Red River Department (Abridged), 1806. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0024</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">44</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">parties push their sticks forward in a manner to overtake the ball but not to check <span class="AddHand-editors">[its]</span> course.  They then examine at what particular <span class="AddHand-editors">[no]</span>tch on bunch the ball rests and count accordingly.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The greater part of the Indians in this quarter are without the first joints of several of their fingers<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Some have entire fingers defficient particularly of the left hand.  This amputation is performed with the Iron of an arrow during their days of penitence &#8212; which days are explained in the following manner.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">When a Young man has attained the age of Twenty he directs his course towards a certain high hill a days march from the Village<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[U]</span>pon this hill he remains as long as his strength will permit for he neither eats, drinks <span class="AddHand-author">nor sleeps</span> but is continually howling and uttering sad Lamentations and it is here he makes a Sacrifice of his fingers when he returns he run<span class="AddHand-author">s</span> full speed down the hill<span class="AddHand-editors">[,]</span> and is met at the entrance of the Village by a particular friend appointed to keep an account of the number of days which he had been absent and for which he had provided as many</p>
<p style="text-align:right;"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Bulls</span></p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[48]</span></p>

